commits.message:
Rototill the build to be entirely Docker driven

Our build configuration was originally written before multi-stage Docker
builds and for Docker Hub. Since Docker Hub had no caching of
intermediate images and we wanted to generate the smallest images
possible, there was no advantage to writing a Dockerfile that was
cacheable.

Now that we have a native dependency with a heavyweight build, we would
benefit significantly from a build that could cache intermediate steps,
and with GitHub Actions and multi-stage builds, we can do that.

Switch to the docker/build-push-action, which among other things,
supports the GitHub Actions Cache API, and use that for both test and
build. Additionally, switch to the GitHub Container Registry, which
allows us to eliminate a shared secret for authentication (since GitHub
provides an authentication token as part of the GitHub Actions
workflow). Finally, enabling the new docker/setup-buildx-action means
that we can lightly parallelize the two stages of the build.

Fixes #494.

crt-aperture.glsl

xbr-lv2-noblend.glsl
xbr-lv3.glsl
yee64.glsl
yeetron.glsl
zfast_crt.glsl

They all need `[sdl] output = opengl`, but some work best with `openglnb`, others need softer input `opengl`, and some look best with integer scaling, so `openglpp`.  

Another thing to note is that most shaders multiply up from the original resolution by 2x2 but others go up by 4x4.  The nuance here is that composite mode itself acts somehwhat like a shader, in that it already runs at double the original 320x200 resolution: so you're "starting" with a 640x400 or 640x480 image, and then going up from there.

issue.title: Run Prettify pre-commit hook
issue.body:
Run Prettier on the three major sections (contract, web-client, web-server) as a Git pre-commit hook

Closes #31

Includes:

- Add Prettier to the “web-server” project -- and also run Prettier on those files. With minor Prettier tweaks for existing `contract` and `web-client`.
- Install Husky and pre-commit hook to root of project (with a new package.json file) which runs Prettier for all 3 sections.

Note that I run `yarn` to ensure all 3 projects have dependencies installed for running Prettier in each project.

comment.body:
To optimize this, another strategy could be to centralize `prettier` in the root and call that with in the pre-commit hook like this:

```
#!/bin/sh
. "$(dirname "$0")/_/husky.sh"

npx prettier --config=./contract/.prettierrc.json --ignore-path ./contract/.prettierignore --write contract
npx prettier --config=./web-client/.prettierrc.json --ignore-path ./web-client/.prettierignore --write web-client
npx prettier --config=./web-server/.prettierrc.json --ignore-path ./web-server/.prettierignore --write web-server
```

and then remove Prettier as a dependency in each package.

Though for `web-client` there are additional Vue linting steps in addition to Prettier.

It just might be simpler to keep the 3 packages separate, it'll just mean a slower pre-commit check for new repositories (that don't have all the dependencies installed yet).

I'm sticking with simpler for now.

issue.title: Sensible defaults for log driver options
issue.body:
I started filling out the standard issue template, but I'm not sure it quite fits (and my answers kept sounding a bit passive aggressive).

I've had a reoccurring issue with **Docker for Mac** where the disk image grows quickly to fill the allocated space. I've implemented all recommended best practice methods to avoid such issues including regularly running a script which does a thorough prune of everything it can, and running the `docker/desktop-reclaim-space` image. But I still kept occasionally running into the issue, and the only solution was to run **Clean / Purge data**.

After using @justincormack's **nsenter1** image, I noticed that one of my containers had a 96GB+ log file. I was surprised to find that the default logger `max-size` was **-1**. I don't believe it's a sensible default for **Docker for Mac**, especially given that the log file size is hidden away in the VM and isn't shown anywhere in the GUI.

**TLDR:** Can a sensible default value please be set for `log-opts.max-size`, to avoid excessive disk image size.

@dgutov , both `ELPA` and `MELPA` support `info` files auto-generation.

```lisp
  :renames (("doc/" ""))

```

So there's no *need* in adding `info` generation to `Company` `Makefile` for these package archives.

But, probably, it may be handy to have a target for manual `info` generation.
It could be provided as `make info` target, f.i., or/and added to `make package` and/or `make elpa` targets.
[BTW, is there any reason to keep supporting both `make package` and `make elpa`?]

Also, optionally, other packages often publish the same manual(s) for on-line access.

issue.title: "Apply & Restart" button is off-screen when System Preferences is set to Larger Text
issue.body:
macOS 11.4, System Preferences / Displays / Scaled is set to "Larger text".  Hardware is a 2019 MacBook, System Report says the built-in LCD is "3072x1920 Retina".  The system does have an external monitor, but under Accessibility I set the external monitor to show a magnified view of the built-in LCD.

Under these circumstances, Docker Desktop v3.5.1 produces a window that is a little too large for the screen.  It does not allow the window to be resized any smaller.  Most of it can still be accessed, but today I found that under Settings / Resources, if I change the RAM size, the setting does not take effect unless I press a button labelled "Apply & Restart", which I did not know existed because it was displayed off-screen.

It is still possible to press the button while it is off-screen: after sliding the RAM control to where I wanted it, I pressed Tab 5 times and Enter, and the setting took effect.  So I'm all set, but I thought you might still like to know this happened.  Thanks.

    • Array.prototype.toSpliced
    • Array.prototype.with

issue.title: longhorn instance-manager pdb preventing eks cluster node replacement/removal
issue.body:
### Describe the bug
longhorn instance-manager pdb preventing eks cluster node replacement


### To Reproduce
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
Attempt any change to an EKS cluster launch template that requires node replacement
In my case I need to change my eks node launch tempalte to add default metadata hop limit to 2 to support IMDSv2 (https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2020/08/amazon-eks-supports-ec2-instance-metadata-service-v2/)
but the same problem happens on an attempt to just downscale node count due to reduced capacity need

in AWS EKS ui, initiate an EKS compute launch template version change. After a time this will fail with cloudwatch showing messages like :- 

requestURI | /api/v1/namespaces/longhorn-system/pods/instance-manager-e-d6f35f61/eviction?timeout=19s
responseObject.message | Cannot evict pod as it would violate the pod's disruption budget.
retry | 20


### Expected behavior
Longhorn allows workloads to be moved to new (replacement) nodes that EKS spins up and allows termination of instance-manager on the nodes tainted for termination


### Environment
Longhorn version: master (12/23/2021)
Kubernetes distro (e.g. RKE/K3s/EKS/OpenShift) and version: EKS v1.21
Number of worker node in the cluster: 6
Additional context
Longhorn needs to allow for cluster node termination as this can happen in cluster lifecycle for a variety of reasons.

  • Added structuredClone method from the HTML spec, see MDN
    • Includes all cases of cloning and transferring of required ECMAScript and platform types that can be polyfilled, for the details see the caveats
    • Uses native structured cloning algorithm implementations where it's possible
    • Includes the new semantic of errors cloning from html/5749
  • Added DOMException polyfill, the Web IDL spec, see MDN
    • Includes DOMException and its attributes polyfills with fixes of many different engines bugs
    • Includes DOMException#stack property polyfill in engines that should have it
    • Reuses native DOMException implementations where it's possible (for example, in old NodeJS where it's not exposed as global)
  • Added support of cause on all Error types
  • Added Error.prototype.toString method polyfill with fixes of many different bugs of JS engines
  • Added Number.prototype.toExponential method polyfill with fixes of many different bugs of JS engines
  • Array grouping proposal:
    • Moved to the stage 3
    • Added Array.prototype.groupByToMap method
    • Removed @@species support

    • Array.prototype.toReversed

    • Array.prototype.toSpliced
    • Array.prototype.with

  • Added Function.prototype.unThis stage 0 proposal
